{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cache keys generated from identical query parameters are always identical, and keys from different parameters never collide.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is key-derivation logic itself (canonicalization/hash), which can be exercised as a pure function with no I/O. The behavior text is only about parameter-to-key determinism/collision, not DB/network/process interaction, so higher levels are not required.","test_description":"Call the key-generation function with repeated identical parameter sets (including different field orderings if supported) and assert identical keys; call with many distinct parameter sets and assert no collisions in the tested domain.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is rule-application logic: category + config -> TTL. A unit test with an injected config map catches real mis-mapping/math errors. Rejected Integration because behavior text does not require config file loading or cross-module runtime handoff; rejected higher levels because no OS/network/LLM dependency is described.","test_description":"Test TTL computation function with categories and freshness-rule config values, asserting exact durations and fallback/default handling for unknown categories.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is typically at module handoff: memory-usage source + threshold config + strategy selector in the cache manager. Unit-testing only selector logic can miss wiring/state-update bugs. Rejected System because behavior text does not require real OS memory probes; an in-process memory metric source can reproduce the boundary.","test_description":"Wire cache manager, config provider, and memory-usage provider (in-process fake). Drive usage below/above threshold and assert active strategy transitions LRU->LFU exactly per config.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on real PostgreSQL write effects and cache invalidation propagation across process/service boundaries. Mocks can hide transaction timing, trigger/notification, and commit-order failures. Rejected Integration because the behavior text names the underlying PostgreSQL table write as the causal event.","test_description":"Run against a real PostgreSQL instance and real cache layer. Seed cache entries, execute INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE on target rows, then assert matching keys are invalidated after commit while unrelated keys remain.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is policy correctness for eviction ordering/counting, usually within policy data structures. No real OS/network/subprocess is needed for the failure described. Rejected Integration because behavior text is about policy semantics, not cross-module propagation.","test_description":"For LRU and LFU policy objects, construct deterministic access patterns to fill capacity, trigger eviction, and assert exact victim keys selected by each policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
